Chapter XLIX Conquest Of Italy By The Franks . 
There is nothing perhaps more adverse to nature and reason than to hold in obedience remote countries and foreign nations , in opposition to their inclination and interest . 
Far different was the situation of the German Caesars , who were ambitious to enslave the kingdom of Italy . 
This irregular tyranny might contend on equal terms with the petty tyrants of Italy nor can the people , or the reader , be much interested in the event of the quarrel . 
But in the eleventh and twelfth centuries , the Lombards rekindled the flame of industry and freedom and the generous example was at length imitated by the republics of Tuscany . 
But their rapid progress , the daily extension of their power and pretensions , were founded on the numbers and spirit of these rising communities . 
After boiling away the flesh . 
