Chapter LIII Fate Of The Eastern Empire . 
In his transactions of business , Liutprand , bishop of Cremona , asserted the free spirit of a Frank and the dignity of his master Otho . 
Yet his sincerity cannot disguise the abasement of his first audience . 
When he approached the throne , the birds of the golden tree began to warble their notes , which were accompanied by the roarings of the two lions of gold . 
With his two companions Liutprand was compelled to bow and to fall prostrate and thrice to touch the ground with his forehead . 
At his first audience , he offered the gifts of his master , slaves , and golden vases , and costly armor . 
On the eve of these processions , the gracious or devout intention of the monarch was proclaimed by the heralds . 
The task of applause was not abandoned to the rude and spontaneous voices of the crowd . 
From either side they echoed in responsive melody the praises of the emperor their poets and musicians directed the choir , and long life and victory were the burden of every song . 
