How elegant is the Greek tongue , even in the mouth of Cedrenus ! Chapter LIV Origin And Doctrine Of The Paulicians . 
As a favor , or punishment , he transplanted them from the banks of the Euphrates to Constantinople and Thrace and by this emigration their doctrine was introduced and diffused in Europe . 
If the sectaries of the metropolis were soon mingled with the promiscuous mass , those of the country struck a deep root in a foreign soil . 
In the tenth century , they were restored and multiplied by a more powerful colony , which John Zimisces transported from the Chalybian hills to the valleys of Mount Haemus . 
The same spirit rendered them arrogant and contumacious they were easily provoked by caprice or injury and their privileges were often violated by the faithless bigotry of the government and clergy . 
In the midst of the Norman war , two thousand five hundred Manichaeans deserted the standard of Alexius Comnenus , and retired to their native homes . 
He dissembled till the moment of revenge invited the chiefs to a friendly conference and punished the innocent and guilty by imprisonment , confiscation , and baptism . 
But the proud hope of eradicating the prejudices of a nation was speedily overturned by the invincible zeal of the Paulicians , who ceased to dissemble or refused to obey . 
After the departure and death of Alexius , they soon resumed their civil and religious laws . 
resided on the confines of Bulgaria , Croatia , and Dalmatia , and governed , by his vicars , the filial congregations of Italy and France . 
