The former was a respectable prelate , alike qualified for this world and the next . 
His experience and riches gave him a strong ascendant in the Christian camp , whose distress he was often able , and sometimes willing , to relieve . 
But it was easier for him to extort the praise of the Infidels , than to preserve the love of his subjects and associates . 
If Raymond was the first to enlist and the last to depart , the delay may be excused by the greatness of his preparation and the promise of an everlasting farewell . 
It is in the person of this Norman chief that we may seek for the coolest policy and ambition , with a small allay of religious fanaticism . 
Several princes of the Norman race accompanied this veteran general and his cousin Tancred was the partner , rather than the servant , of the war . 
